 <!-- Introduction -->
 <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
 <p class="text-xl text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-8">USB-C Power Delivery has become the universal charging standard. Yet many buyers still confuse PD with Quick Charge, misunderstand wattage tiers, or source the wrong chargers for their market. This guide cuts through the jargon to help you source the right USB-C products with confidence.</p>
 
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">This guide covers everything B2B buyers need to know about USB-C, from technical specifications to sourcing the right <a href="/products/gan-charger/" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange font-bold">GaN chargers</a>, <a href="/products/power-bank/" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange font-bold">power banks</a>, and <a href="/products/car-charger/" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange font-bold">car chargers</a> for your inventory.</p>

 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">PD 3.1's Extended Power Range (EPR) at 240W is opening new applications beyond phones and laptops. High-performance workstations, gaming laptops, monitors, and even industrial equipment can now be powered through a single USB-C cable. The 101-240W power bracket is the fastest-growing segment at <strong>21.95% CAGR</strong> (<a href="https://www.yolegroup.com/strategy-insights/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange">Yole Group</a>, 2025), while the broader PD charger market grows at 4.8%. Asia-Pacific leads with ~35% market share, followed by North America at ~30% and Europe at ~26% (QYResearch, 2025). Key players in the PD IC space include Texas Instruments, Infineon, STMicroelectronics, and Chinese leaders like Southchip and Chipsea.</p>
 </div>

