 <path d="M434.8 70.1c14.3 10.4 17.5 30.4 7.1 44.7l-256 352c-5.5 7.6-14 12.3-23.4 13.1s-18.5-2.7-25.1-9.3l-128-128c-12.5-12.5-12.5-32.8 0-45.3s32.8-12.5 45.3 0l101.5 101.5 234-321.7c10.4-14.3 30.4-17.5 44.7-7.1z" fill="currentColor"/>
 </svg><span><strong>Regional certifications:</strong> CE, FCC, RoHS depending on your target market.</span></li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">"The most common mistake I see buyers make is assuming all PD chargers are the same," says Nina Nico, OEM Technical Lead at WOWOHCOOL. "The difference between a charger with genuine USB-IF certification and one without shows up in compatibility testing, especially with Samsung PPS and MacBook extended power range requirements. Always request the USB-IF TID (Trademark ID) to verify certification."</p>

 <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 md:p-8 mb-8 mt-8 border border-slate-200">
 <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 uppercase mb-4">How to Verify a USB-IF TID in 3 Steps</h3>
 <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-600 text-sm">
 <li><strong>Request the TID</strong>, ask the supplier for the Test ID (typically formatted as <code class="bg-white px-1 rounded border border-slate-200">5XXX</code> or <code class="bg-white px-1 rounded border border-slate-200">TID-5XXX</code>) for the exact PD product you intend to source.</li>
 <li><strong>Search the database</strong>, open the <a href="https://www.usb.org/products" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange font-semibold">USB-IF Certified Products database</a>, filter by Certified PD Products, and enter the TID.</li>
 <li><strong>Confirm the manufacturer</strong>, the listed company name must match the supplier's legal entity. A mismatch means the supplier is reselling another factory's certified design, which transfers compliance risk to your brand.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>

