 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">7. Conclusion: The Future of USB-C PD</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">USB-C Power Delivery continues to evolve as the universal charging standard. With PD 3.1 supporting up to 240W and GaN technology making chargers smaller and more efficient, the landscape for B2B buyers is full of opportunity. Understanding these technologies helps you make informed sourcing decisions that benefit your brand and customers.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">As USB-C adoption accelerates across smartphones, laptops, tablets, and even power tools, PD 3.1 with GaN technology positions your brand at the forefront of the charging market. Products that support Extended Power Range (EPR) up to 48V will be increasingly in demand as more devices adopt USB-C as their primary power port.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">According to the USB Implementers Forum (USB-IF, 2025), over 4 billion USB-C devices have been shipped globally, with PD 3.1 adoption growing 50% year-over-year. This installed base represents an enormous addressable market for brands developing PD 3.1 compatible chargers and accessories. For a detailed look at how GaN V (fifth-generation gallium nitride) technology maximizes PD 3.1 performance in compact charger designs, see our <a href="/blog/gan-v-charger-oem-manufacturing" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">GaN V charger OEM manufacturing guide</a>.</p>
